      content: "Large PDFs can be unwieldy. You might only need a few pages from a 100-page document, or you want to separate different sections into individual files. Manually doing this is tedious and time-consuming.\n\nThe Split PDF tool solves this instantly. Upload your document and choose which pages you want to extract. You can take a single page, a range of pages, or specific pages scattered throughout the document. The tool creates separate PDFs for each section you want, letting you keep what matters and discard the rest.\n\nThis is perfect when you're sharing documents with others (send only the relevant pages), organizing your files (separate projects into different documents), or cleaning up your library (remove unnecessary pages). It's a simple tool that saves real time and keeps your files lean and focused.\n\nWhy Split PDFs?\nSplitting PDFs solves real problems:\n\n• Sharing: Send only relevant pages, not 200-page documents\n• Organization: Break large files into manageable chunks\n• Focused Content: Create topic-specific documents from comprehensive files\n• Storage: Reduce file count by splitting large combined PDFs\n• Accessibility: Make easier-to-handle files for mobile users\n• Archival: Organize documents by date, project, or topic\n\nWithout splitting, you're stuck sharing enormous files or manually recreating documents.\n\nHow PDF Splitting Works\nWhen you specify which pages to extract, the PDF splitter:\n\n1. Reads your original PDF\n2. Identifies the pages you want to keep\n3. Extracts those pages with all formatting intact\n4. Creates a new PDF containing only selected pages\n5. Discards the unwanted pages\n\nAll original formatting, images, and content are preserved.\n\nStep-by-Step Splitting Process\n1. Visit PDFConvert.tech and select Split PDF\n2. Upload your large PDF\n3. Specify which pages you want:\n   - Enter a page range (1-10)\n   - Enter specific pages (1,3,5,10)\n   - Create multiple splits\n4. Click Split\n5. Download your extracted pages as new PDF(s)\n6. Repeat if you need multiple sections\n\nThe process takes seconds even for massive PDFs.\n\nExtracting Page Ranges\nTo extract pages 15-25 from a document:\n• Simply enter \"15-25\" in the page range field\n• The tool creates a new PDF with those pages\n• All formatting and content transfers perfectly\n\nThis works for any continuous range.\n\nExtracting Specific Pages\nNeed pages 1, 5, 10, and 47?\n• Enter \"1,5,10,47\" (comma-separated)\n• The tool extracts exactly those pages\n• They appear in order in the new PDF\n• Perfect for gathering scattered important pages\n\nPractical Splitting Scenarios\n\nSupporting Documents:\nA 300-page report with 50 pages of appendices. Extract only the main report for distribution, keep appendices separately.\n\nProject Separation:\nOne PDF containing three projects. Split into three separate files, one per project.\n\nChapter Extraction:\nA book PDF split into chapters for easier reading on mobile or for sharing specific chapters.\n\nDocument Isolation:\nA combined file with multiple contracts. Extract and organize each contract separately.\n\nSharing Relevant Sections:\nA comprehensive guide but your colleague only needs pages 35-42. Extract and send just those pages.\n\nRemoving Junk Pages:\nScan dozens of pages, but some are blank or duplicate. Extract only the good pages.\n\nMultiple Splits from One PDF\nYou can split the same PDF multiple ways:\n\n• Split into sections 1-50, 51-100, 101-150 for different stakeholders\n• Extract chapter 3 for one person, chapters 5-7 for another\n• Create project-specific documents from one master file\n\nRepeated splitting from the original takes seconds each time.\n\nPage Numbering Tips\nWhen specifying pages:\n• Pages are numbered starting from 1 (not 0)\n• Verify page count before starting\n• Use the preview feature to confirm you're extracting the right pages\n• When uncertain about page numbers, extract to check first\n\nOrganizing Split Documents\nAfter splitting, organize your new files clearly:\n\n• Name them descriptively: \"Report_Executive_Summary\", \"Report_Appendix_A\"\n• Group related splits in folders\n• Keep originals for reference\n• Archive splits no longer needed\n\nBest Practices\n\n• Preview the page range to confirm correct pages\n• Keep the original PDF for future splits\n• Name split files clearly\n• Verify content is intact after splitting\n• Don't delete originals until certain you won't need them again\n• Consider combining related splits back together if needed\n\nTroubleshooting\n\nWrong pages extracted:\nDouble-check your page numbers. Pages might be counted differently than expected.\n\nBlank pages in result:\nThe source PDF might have blank pages. These are extracted as-is.\n\nFormatting looks odd:\nThis is rare, but certain PDFs with complex layouts might display unexpectedly.\n\nCan't extract specific pages:\nSome password-protected PDFs prevent splitting. Unprotect first if possible.\n\nAdvanced Splitting\nBeyond basic splitting:\n\n• Extract and then compress for easier sharing\n• Split and then merge selected sections with other PDFs\n• Extract pages and convert to images\n• Split and password-protect sensitive sections\n\nThis flexibility makes PDFConvert.tech's Split tool incredibly versatile.\n\nAlternatives to Splitting\nSometimes splitting isn't the best approach:\n\n• For minor edits: Just share the whole file\n• For multiple versions: Consider versioning control\n• For collaboration: Use shared document tools\n• For heavy editing: Convert to editable format first\n\nConclusion\nSplitting PDFs is straightforward with the right tool. What might seem complicated—extracting pages from a large document—becomes a quick process that results in focused, manageable files.\n\nStop sharing massive PDFs when your recipient only needs a few pages. Start splitting, and you'll immediately appreciate how much cleaner and more professional your document workflow becomes."
